\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Empirical evidence seems to suggest optimal not to enforce
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Contrary to intuition about the benefit of having free contracts
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Theoretical work has less clear conclusions 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But what about spillovers?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Most charitably: non-enforcing states 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

do better
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 than enforcing states, and states 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

do better
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 when they exogenously switch from enforcement to non-enforcement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Crowding out
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 story: brain drain to non-enforcing regimes after exogenous shift to enforcing
 regime (Marx 2015)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
How to rule out this explanation?
\end_layout

